explanation: To decide whether the if-controlling expression is invariant you must know what values 'return_code' can take and whether any of those values are compile-time constants. - OS_FileSys_Initialize: the function that sets return_code; you need its prototype/implementation or documentation to know whether it can produce different return values (i.e. whether the call is non-constant or always yields a fixed value). - OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE and OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS: the two constants used in the if-condition; you must confirm their definitions (constant values and types) to determine if the comparison can ever be true or is effectively a constant expression. - OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE: assigned inside the if; needed to ensure the assignment does not affect the controlling expression elsewhere and to check type/compatibility with return_code. - int32 (typedef): type of the function return and return_code; required to understand integer type semantics (signedness/width) for comparisons and constant-expression determination. - osal_blockcount_t (typedef): part of the called function signature (OS_FileSys_Initialize); include to fully resolve that function's declaration if needed when inspecting its implementation or stub behavior. - false (boolean literal/macro): argument passed to OS_FileSys_Initialize; included so the called function prototype/implementation can be resolved completely (helps if overload/stub behavior depends on this parameter).
